title: Duke up to No. 22 AP Poll; UNC just outside
text:
Duke up to No. 22 AP Poll; UNC just outside 
Posted 2:02 p.m. today Your friends e-mail addresses (comma separated): * Subject: * You must enter the characters with black color that stand out from the other characters More on this No. 6 Clemson hands Miami worst loss ever, 58-0 
Duke rose one spot in this week's AP Poll to No. 22 after beating Virginia Tech 45-43 in four overtimes in the ACC's longest game in history. 
North Carolina (6-1, 3-0 ACC) did not crack the Top 25 after a 26-13 win against Virginia , but their 46 votes place them at an extrapolated No. 27. 
Appalachian State (6-1, 3-0 Sun Belt) also received six votes after this week's nationally televised win against Georgia Southern . placing them at No. 33 in the nation. The Mountaineers will host Troy next week before taking on the conference's second best team in primetime on Nov. 5, Arkansas State. AP Top 25 College Football Poll 
As for the rest of the ACC, Clemson (which comes into Carter-Finley Saturday to play NC State Saturday) jumped from No. 6 to No.3 after shutting out Miami 58-0 for the Hurricanes' worst loss in program history. Pitt (which hosts the Tar Heels Thursday night at 7 p.m.) bettered itself two spots to No. 23, by improving to 4-0 in the Coastal Division with a 23-20 win against Syracuse. Florida State is down eight spots -- from No. 9 to No. 17 -- after its loss to Georgia Tech at the hands of a block-six thriller. 
Top-ranked Ohio State has picked up 11 first-place votes following Utah's first loss of the season. 
The Buckeyes (8-0) have been No. 1 all season, but had been losing first-place votes in recent weeks. This week, Ohio State had 39 first-place votes in the poll released Sunday after routing Rutgers. 
Baylor, Clemson, LSU and TCU — the rest of the top 5 — also received first-place votes, as did No. 7 Alabama. 
Utah had its highest regular-season ranking after climbing to No. 3 last week, but dropped 10 spots after losing to unranked Southern California. 
UCLA (No. 24) and Mississippi State (No. 25) each climbed back into the polls with Texas A&M and Cal each folling tout following losses.
